answers.body_markdown:
You can try [Flux#generate][1] and [Queue#peek][2]. Just keep in mind that `peek` will return `null` if the queue is empty, and it cannot be used in `onNext`.

Something like:
```java
Flux.generate(sink -&gt; {
    val element = queue.peek();
    if (element == null) {
        sink.complete();
    } else {
        sink.next(element);
    }
});
```

There is also [Flux#repeatWhen][3] operator, in case you want to re-subscribe to the queue after it was considered empty, e.g. with:
```java
flux.repeatWhen(it -&gt; it.delayElements(ofSeconds(1)))
```


  [1]: https://projectreactor.io/docs/core/release/api/reactor/core/publisher/Flux.html#generate-java.util.concurrent.Callable-java.util.function.BiFunction-
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Queue.html#peek()
  [3]: https://projectreactor.io/docs/core/release/api/reactor/core/publisher/Flux.html#repeatWhen-java.util.function.Function-

