You&#39;re getting the following error:

&gt; &#39;Person()&#39; has private access in &#39;android.app.Person&#39;

Because there is no way you can create a new instance of the `Person` class. Why? because the constructor of the class is private:

    private Person() {
        throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Stub!&quot;);
    }

So in order to write an object in the Realtime Database, the class should contain a public no-argument constructor. That being said, to solve this issue,  you have to create your own Person class. At a minimum, it should look like this:

    class Person {
        String name;
    }

In which the constructor is provided by the JVM, or if you want to use encapsulation:

    class Person {
        private String name;

        public Person() {} //&#128072;

        Person(String name) {
            this.name = name;
        }

        void setName(String name) {
            this.name = name;
