Computer programmers start counting at `0` (not `1`). Change `int i = 1;` to `int i = 0;`, second I would make the test and assignment of `tmp` to `p` in the `while` loop condition. I would also use formatted output over string concatenation. Like,

	public static int nbYear(int p0, double percent, int aug, int p) {
		System.out.printf(&quot;p0: %d, percent: %.2f, aug: %d, p: %d%n&quot;,
				p0, percent, aug, p);
		double tmp = p0;
		int i = 0;
		while ((tmp = tmp * (1 + (percent / 100)) + aug) &lt;= p) {
			System.out.println(&quot;running total: &quot; + tmp);
			i++;
		}
		return i;
	}

In java arrays are represented by square brackets:
```java
String [] programmingLanguages = ...
```
You can initialize in-place:
```java
String [] programmingLanguages = {&quot;C&quot;, &quot;C++&quot;, &quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Lua&quot;};
```

Or initialize by index:

```java
String [] programmingLanguages = new String [4];
programmingLanguages[0] = &quot;C&quot;;
programmingLanguages[1] = &quot;C++&quot;;
programmingLanguages[2] = &quot;Java&quot;;
programmingLanguages[3] = &quot;Lua&quot;;
```

